Fig. 2
a shows the bulk contents of nickel species determined by ICP analysis of the Ni-DML-x-4-1 samples, where x = 100–160 °C. Similar to the results obtained from the STEM-EDS analysis described above, the Ni content in the samples increased proportionally with the hydrothermal temperature. Based on the elemental analysis, the framework compositions of Ni-DML were calculated assuming the 72 T-atoms of the MWW unit cell (Table 1
). According to the proposed single-step delamination and nickel substitution mechanism [31], it can be assumed that at relatively low temperatures (i.e., 100 °C and 120 °C), some Ni atoms are substituted at the framework sites wherein B atoms are removed, and some remain as defect sites. However, at relatively high temperatures (i.e., 140 °C and 160 °C), more than one Ni atoms may exist at the extraframework per substituted Ni framework atom. Accordingly, the Si/NiFramework ratio of Ni-DML-160-4-1 approached 10.4 with increasing the three synthesis variables (Tables 1 and S1).
